This certainly makes sense and it <i>is</i> useful. But that's not the use of <i>auto</i> i was referring to. This one is:<p><pre><code>  auto func(int x) -> double;
</code></pre>
I realize that the above is allowed primarily for this case:<p><pre><code>  auto func(int x) -> decltype(x);
</code></pre>
but from a casual examination the following - simpler and cleaner - notation can quite easily be made unambiguous:<p><pre><code>  decltype(x) func(int x);
</code></pre>
Also, isn't <i>typeof</i> a more natural name for <i>decltype</i> ? Again I realize that the keyword overlaps with existing gcc extension, but semantics of latter is a subset of C++0x one.
